{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_dictionaries",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Dictionary Basics",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A dictionary stores data in **key-value pairs**. Instead of using positions like lists, you use meaningful **keys** to access values."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Think of it like a real dictionary - you look up a word (key) to find its definition (value)."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "creating_dictionaries",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Creating Dictionaries",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You create a dictionary using **curly braces** `{}`. Each key-value pair is separated by a comma `,` and the key and value are separated by a colon `:`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "student = {\n    \"name\": \"Alice\",\n    \"age\": 20,\n    \"grade\": \"A\"\n}\nprint(student)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "{'name': 'Alice', 'age': 20, 'grade': 'A'}"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "This dictionary has three keys: `\"name\"`, `\"age\"`, and `\"grade\"`, each with its own value."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "key_value_concept",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The **key** is what you use to look up data. The **value** is the actual data stored."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "phone_book = {\n    \"Alice\": \"555-1234\",\n    \"Bob\": \"555-5678\",\n    \"Charlie\": \"555-9012\"\n}\nprint(phone_book)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "{'Alice': '555-1234', 'Bob': '555-5678', 'Charlie': '555-9012'}"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Names are the keys, phone numbers are the values."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_create",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "code_fill",
                    "content": "Create a dictionary called `car` with key `\"brand\"` and value `\"Toyota\"`.",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "lines": [
                            {
                                "code": "car = {1}",
                                "indent": 0,
                                "blank": "1"
                            },
                            {
                                "code": "print(car)",
                                "indent": 0
                            }
                        ],
                        "options": [
                            "[\"brand\": \"Toyota\"]",
                            "{\"brand\": \"Toyota\"}",
                            "(\"brand\": \"Toyota\")"
                        ],
                        "solutions": {
                            "1": "{\"brand\": \"Toyota\"}"
                        },
                        "hint": "Use curly braces {} with key: value format.",
                        "correctFeedback": "Perfect! You created a dictionary with curly braces.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "Use curly braces {} and separate key and value with a colon.",
                        "explanation": "Dictionaries use curly braces {} and colons : to separate keys and values.",
                        "output": "{'brand': 'Toyota'}"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "accessing_values",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Accessing Values",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "To get a value from a dictionary, use the **key** inside square brackets."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "student = {\"name\": \"Alice\", \"age\": 20}\nprint(student[\"name\"])\nprint(student[\"age\"])",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Alice\n20"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Using the key `\"name\"` gives us `\"Alice\"`, and `\"age\"` gives us `20`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "keys_not_indices",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Important:** Dictionaries don't use numeric indices like lists. You use the actual key name."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "colors = {\n    \"primary\": \"red\",\n    \"secondary\": \"blue\"\n}\nprint(colors[\"primary\"])",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "red"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can't use `colors[0]` - you must use the key `\"primary\"`."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_access",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "code_fill",
                    "content": "Get the value for key `\"city\"` from the dictionary.",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "lines": [
                            {
                                "code": "person = {\"name\": \"John\", \"city\": \"NYC\"}",
                                "indent": 0
                            },
                            {
                                "code": "location = person[{1}]",
                                "indent": 0,
                                "blank": "1"
                            },
                            {
                                "code": "print(location)",
                                "indent": 0
                            }
                        ],
                        "options": [
                            "city",
                            "\"city\"",
                            "1"
                        ],
                        "solutions": {
                            "1": "\"city\""
                        },
                        "hint": "Use the key name in quotes to access the value.",
                        "correctFeedback": "Perfect! You accessed the value using the key \"city\".",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "Use the key in quotes: person[\"city\"]",
                        "explanation": "Dictionary keys must be in quotes when accessing values.",
                        "output": "NYC"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_access_output",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "What will this code print?"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "prices = {\"apple\": 1.50, \"banana\": 0.75}\nprint(prices[\"banana\"])",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "mcq",
